{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Do focused WEB research (WebSearch + WebFetch; cite URLs) for a safety-critical design decision in a local self-evolving agent (\"Yogi\", Rust). Do not answer from memory alone.\n\nCONTEXT: Yogi has a CLOSED, type-enforced mutation surface — a being can edit only declarative genome fields (prompt, tool/retrieval/decomposition/routing policies, install/revoke skills, reasoning-navigator/domain-model refs) via a pure `apply()`. It can NOT grant itself capabilities, edit trust policy, or run arbitrary code. M4 adds an `Improver` that PROPOSES genome mutations, gated by a \"Two-Gate Policy\": a Validation Gate (a mutation is accepted only if measured improvement exceeds noise) and a Capacity Gate (the edited hypothesis class must stay within a bounded capacity). The verifier signal is the M2 falsification bench (pass/fail).\n\nDECISION: how to design this bounded self-modification safely and concretely. Research:\n1. **Self-improving / self-modifying agent systems & their guardrails:** OPRO, EvoPrompt, PromptBreeder, STOP (Self-Taught Optimizer), Gödel Agent / Darwin-Gödel Machine, SEAL, and any 2024-2026 work on agents editing their own prompts/policies. What guardrails do they use; what failure modes appeared (e.g. \"objective hacking\" / reward tampering / misevolution — Shao et al. \"Your Agent May Misevolve\")?\n2. **The Validation Gate concretely:** statistical acceptance of a self-edit — regression detection, A/B with significance, BOCPD/changepoint, hold-out evaluation. How to decide \"improvement exceeds noise\" with small samples; avoid accepting noise.\n3. **The Capacity Gate concretely:** what does \"bounded capacity / VC-dimension stays bounded under self-modification\" mean operationally for a system editing prompts/policies (not weights)? Is there a practical proxy (mutation size limits, edit-distance caps, complexity budgets, a fixed schema) that approximates the theory? Cite the utility-learning-tension / learnability-under-self-modification literature if it exists.\n4. **Self-judgment bias:** when an LLM evaluates its own mutations it inflates scores. Mitigations (separate evaluator model/temperature, rubric scoring, calibration tracking, held-out verifier). \n5. **Rollback / reversibility:** keeping every self-edit reversible and audited.\n\nEND WITH a concrete RECOMMENDATION for Yogi M4: how to implement the Improver + Validation Gate + Capacity Gate + bias mitigation + rollback over a closed declarative mutation surface, with the bench as verifier. Cite URLs throughout. Return findings only; do not edit files."},"uuid":"188559ad-67f9-4c26-b392-4deabf9752f9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:14:56.668Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
