{"parentUuid":"5fc91d31-93c2-4139-b685-ae1028bbe8b6","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01P8YrLT6YnCuVSjoX5hzJXh","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"\"Your Agent May Misevolve\" Shao misevolution self-evolving LLM agent\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2509.26354v1] Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.26354v1\"},{\"title\":\"[2509.26354] Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.26354\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - ShaoShuai0605/Misevolution: Official Repo of Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ShaoShuai0605/Misevolution\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/396048699_Your_Agent_May_Misevolve_Emergent_Risks_in_Self-evolving_LLM_Agents\"},{\"title\":\"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.26354\"},{\"title\":\"Paper page - Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2509.26354\"},{\"title\":\"[Literature Review] Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/your-agent-may-misevolve-emergent-risks-in-self-evolving-llm-agents\"},{\"title\":\"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-Evolving LLM Agents | by Dixon | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@huguosuo/your-agent-may-misevolve-emergent-risks-in-self-evolving-llm-agents-2f364a6de72e\"},{\"title\":\"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/pdf/04f75a91f35d7ca6f6b800142d713f123f9dba04.pdf\"}]\n\nI've found the research paper you're looking for. Here's what the search results show:\n\n## Overview\n\n\"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\" is a paper by Shuai Shao and 10 other authors.\n\n## Key Concepts\n\nThe paper studies the case where an agent's self-evolution deviates in unintended ways, leading to undesirable or even harmful outcomes, referring to this as \"Misevolution\".\n\n## Research Methodology\n\nThe researchers evaluate misevolution along four key evolutionary pathways: model, memory, tool, and workflow.\n\n## Main Findings\n\nThe empirical findings reveal that misevolution is a widespread risk, affecting agents built even on top-tier LLMs (e.g., Gemini-2.5-Pro). More specifically, a memory-evolving coding agent based on Qwen3-Coder-480B showed a 55% reduction in Refusal Rate after several evolutionary cycles, and tool-evolving agents built on top-tier LLMs would generate and reuse tools with potential vulnerabilities in over 76% of cases, and fail to identify and reject malicious external tools nearly 84% of the time.\n\n## Significance\n\nThis is the first study to systematically conceptualize misevolution and provide empirical evidence of its occurrence, highlighting an urgent need for new safety paradigms for self-evolving agents.\n\nThe paper's code and data are available on GitHub at https://github.com/ShaoShuai0605/Misevolution.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"57890951-da58-4b08-b0eb-491d7025bf66","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:15.607Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"\"Your Agent May Misevolve\" Shao misevolution self-evolving LLM agent","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01HLRrvJZ8zh5UshDnFHwFmb","content":[{"title":"[2509.26354v1] Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.26354v1"},{"title":"[2509.26354] Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.26354"},{"title":"GitHub - ShaoShuai0605/Misevolution: Official Repo of Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/ShaoShuai0605/Misevolution"},{"title":"(PDF) Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/396048699_Your_Agent_May_Misevolve_Emergent_Risks_in_Self-evolving_LLM_Agents"},{"title":"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.26354"},{"title":"Paper page - Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2509.26354"},{"title":"[Literature Review] Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents","url":"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/your-agent-may-misevolve-emergent-risks-in-self-evolving-llm-agents"},{"title":"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-Evolving LLM Agents | by Dixon | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@huguosuo/your-agent-may-misevolve-emergent-risks-in-self-evolving-llm-agents-2f364a6de72e"},{"title":"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents","url":"https://openreview.net/pdf/04f75a91f35d7ca6f6b800142d713f123f9dba04.pdf"}]},"I've found the research paper you're looking for. Here's what the search results show:\n\n## Overview\n\n\"Your Agent May Misevolve: Emergent Risks in Self-evolving LLM Agents\" is a paper by Shuai Shao and 10 other authors.\n\n## Key Concepts\n\nThe paper studies the case where an agent's self-evolution deviates in unintended ways, leading to undesirable or even harmful outcomes, referring to this as \"Misevolution\".\n\n## Research Methodology\n\nThe researchers evaluate misevolution along four key evolutionary pathways: model, memory, tool, and workflow.\n\n## Main Findings\n\nThe empirical findings reveal that misevolution is a widespread risk, affecting agents built even on top-tier LLMs (e.g., Gemini-2.5-Pro). More specifically, a memory-evolving coding agent based on Qwen3-Coder-480B showed a 55% reduction in Refusal Rate after several evolutionary cycles, and tool-evolving agents built on top-tier LLMs would generate and reuse tools with potential vulnerabilities in over 76% of cases, and fail to identify and reject malicious external tools nearly 84% of the time.\n\n## Significance\n\nThis is the first study to systematically conceptualize misevolution and provide empirical evidence of its occurrence, highlighting an urgent need for new safety paradigms for self-evolving agents.\n\nThe paper's code and data are available on GitHub at https://github.com/ShaoShuai0605/Misevolution."],"durationSeconds":7.965366792000132,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5fc91d31-93c2-4139-b685-ae1028bbe8b6","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"c2567ee7-d860-4848-9acb-47abc0e23254","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FCnAcqzLVN46irnpB256gh","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Darwin Gödel Machine self-improving agent safety 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"First published: arXiv:2505.22954v1 29 May 2025 Darwin Gödel Machine:\",\"url\":\"https://s-rsa.com/index.php/agi/article/download/15063/11061\"},{\"title\":\"[2505.22954] Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents | SuperIntelligence - Robotics - Safety & Alignment\",\"url\":\"https://s-rsa.com/index.php/agi/article/view/15063\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.22954v2\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/393853947_Darwin_Godel_Machine_Open-Ended_Evolution_of_Self-Improving_Agents\"},{\"title\":\"Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954\"}]\n\nI've found comprehensive information about the Darwin Gödel Machine research. Here's what the web search revealed:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Darwin Gödel Machine (DGM) is a self-referential, self-improving system that writes and modifies its own code to become a better coding agent. The project takes inspiration from Darwinian evolution and investigates the effectiveness of maintaining a library of previously discovered agents to serve as stepping stones for future generations.\n\n## Performance Results\n\nThe DGM automatically improves its coding capabilities (e.g., better code editing tools, long-context window management, peer-review mechanisms), increasing performance on SWE-bench from 20.0% to 50.0%, and on Polyglot from 14.2% to 30.7%.\n\n## Safety Measures\n\nThe research addresses safety concerns proactively. All experiments were done with safety precautions (e.g., sandboxing, human oversight). The researchers note that if evaluation benchmarks do not fully capture all desired agent properties (e.g., safety and robustness), the self-improvement loop could amplify misalignment over successive generations.\n\n## Future Directions\n\nThe DGM could potentially discover and integrate better internal safeguards or modify itself for greater transparency, if such properties were included in its evaluation criteria, suggesting a promising pathway in which self-improvement becomes a tool for building more trustworthy AI systems.\n\nThe paper was first published on arXiv in May 2025 by researchers including Jenny Zhang and Jeff Clune.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"effe9266-8247-40c3-a8aa-c54dda32ecdd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:15.822Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Darwin Gödel Machine self-improving agent safety 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01PKGSjo8BCA3T5jPk8WYYcP","content":[{"title":"First published: arXiv:2505.22954v1 29 May 2025 Darwin Gödel Machine:","url":"https://s-rsa.com/index.php/agi/article/download/15063/11061"},{"title":"[2505.22954] Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.22954"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents | SuperIntelligence - Robotics - Safety & Alignment","url":"https://s-rsa.com/index.php/agi/article/view/15063"},{"title":"Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2505.22954v2"},{"title":"(PDF) Darwin Gödel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/393853947_Darwin_Godel_Machine_Open-Ended_Evolution_of_Self-Improving_Agents"},{"title":"Darwin Godel Machine: Open-Ended Evolution of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954"}]},"I've found comprehensive information about the Darwin Gödel Machine research. Here's what the web search revealed:\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Darwin Gödel Machine (DGM) is a self-referential, self-improving system that writes and modifies its own code to become a better coding agent. The project takes inspiration from Darwinian evolution and investigates the effectiveness of maintaining a library of previously discovered agents to serve as stepping stones for future generations.\n\n## Performance Results\n\nThe DGM automatically improves its coding capabilities (e.g., better code editing tools, long-context window management, peer-review mechanisms), increasing performance on SWE-bench from 20.0% to 50.0%, and on Polyglot from 14.2% to 30.7%.\n\n## Safety Measures\n\nThe research addresses safety concerns proactively. All experiments were done with safety precautions (e.g., sandboxing, human oversight). The researchers note that if evaluation benchmarks do not fully capture all desired agent properties (e.g., safety and robustness), the self-improvement loop could amplify misalignment over successive generations.\n\n## Future Directions\n\nThe DGM could potentially discover and integrate better internal safeguards or modify itself for greater transparency, if such properties were included in its evaluation criteria, suggesting a promising pathway in which self-improvement becomes a tool for building more trustworthy AI systems.\n\nThe paper was first published on arXiv in May 2025 by researchers including Jenny Zhang and Jeff Clune."],"durationSeconds":9.080695707999869,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c2567ee7-d860-4848-9acb-47abc0e23254","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"f3efb491-4396-4c16-838d-90fbc87cc5b1","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Tfkkce5Zney2VZvm4yK7Wq","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"SEAL self-adapting language models MIT self-edits 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"MIT’s SEAL Allows LLMs to Autonomously Learn in Real Time | Educational Technology and Change Journal\",\"url\":\"https://etcjournal.com/2025/10/18/mits-seal-allows-llms-to-autonomously-learn-in-real-time/\"},{\"title\":\"Self-adapting LLMs behave more like students to absorb new knowledge\",\"url\":\"https://techxplore.com/news/2025-11-llms-students-absorb-knowledge.html\"},{\"title\":\"Self-improving language models are becoming reality with MIT's updated SEAL technique | VentureBeat\",\"url\":\"https://venturebeat.com/ai/self-improving-language-models-are-becoming-reality-with-mits-updated-seal\"},{\"title\":\"[2506.10943] Self-Adapting Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.10943\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - Continual-Intelligence/SEAL: Self-Adapting Language Models · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/Continual-Intelligence/SEAL\"},{\"title\":\"MIT Researchers Unveil “SEAL”: A New Step Towards Self-Improving AI | Synced\",\"url\":\"https://syncedreview.com/2025/06/16/mit-researchers-unveil-seal-a-new-step-towards-self-improving-ai/\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Adapting Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.10943v1\"},{\"title\":\"Beyond static AI: MIT's new framework lets models teach themselves | VentureBeat\",\"url\":\"https://venturebeat.com/ai/beyond-static-ai-mits-new-framework-lets-models-teach-themselves\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Adapting Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://jyopari.github.io/posts/seal\"},{\"title\":\"MIT Pushes AI Toward Self-Learning With SEAL Framework | PYMNTS.com\",\"url\":\"https://www.pymnts.com/artificial-intelligence-2/2025/mit-pushes-ai-toward-self-learning-with-seal-framework/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about SEAL:\n\n## SEAL: Self-Adapting Language Models\n\nIn mid-2025, researchers at MIT's Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory (CSAIL) unveiled a groundbreaking technique called SEAL—short for Self-Adapting Language Models.\n\n### How It Works\n\nThis framework enables large language models (LLMs) to autonomously improve themselves by generating and applying their own fine-tuning data. Rather than relying on external retraining or human-curated datasets, SEAL allows models to produce structured \"self-edits\" that include synthetic training examples, optimization instructions, and even gradient-based update directives.\n\nSEAL breaks this constraint by introducing a two-loop system: an inner loop where the model generates its own self-edit in response to new input, and an outer loop where that self-edit is used to fine-tune the model.\n\n### Key Advantages\n\nTraditional LLMs are static once deployed, unable to internalize new knowledge or adapt to novel tasks without manual intervention. SEAL addresses this by using self-edits in supervised fine-tuning, resulting in persistent updates to the model's weights and capabilities.\n\n### Performance Results\n\nOn question answering, SEAL improved model accuracy by nearly 15% and on some skill-learning tasks, it boosted the success rate by more than 50%. Additionally, in few-shot learning tasks, the success rate jumped to 72.5%, up from 20% using self-edits generated without reinforcement learning.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"c428763f-0696-400b-8608-da0f428bcc59","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:16.811Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"SEAL self-adapting language models MIT self-edits 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01E7GMzSKEdYpjhVs9WrXrqS","content":[{"title":"MIT’s SEAL Allows LLMs to Autonomously Learn in Real Time | Educational Technology and Change Journal","url":"https://etcjournal.com/2025/10/18/mits-seal-allows-llms-to-autonomously-learn-in-real-time/"},{"title":"Self-adapting LLMs behave more like students to absorb new knowledge","url":"https://techxplore.com/news/2025-11-llms-students-absorb-knowledge.html"},{"title":"Self-improving language models are becoming reality with MIT's updated SEAL technique | VentureBeat","url":"https://venturebeat.com/ai/self-improving-language-models-are-becoming-reality-with-mits-updated-seal"},{"title":"[2506.10943] Self-Adapting Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.10943"},{"title":"GitHub - Continual-Intelligence/SEAL: Self-Adapting Language Models · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/Continual-Intelligence/SEAL"},{"title":"MIT Researchers Unveil “SEAL”: A New Step Towards Self-Improving AI | Synced","url":"https://syncedreview.com/2025/06/16/mit-researchers-unveil-seal-a-new-step-towards-self-improving-ai/"},{"title":"Self-Adapting Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.10943v1"},{"title":"Beyond static AI: MIT's new framework lets models teach themselves | VentureBeat","url":"https://venturebeat.com/ai/beyond-static-ai-mits-new-framework-lets-models-teach-themselves"},{"title":"Self-Adapting Language Models","url":"https://jyopari.github.io/posts/seal"},{"title":"MIT Pushes AI Toward Self-Learning With SEAL Framework | PYMNTS.com","url":"https://www.pymnts.com/artificial-intelligence-2/2025/mit-pushes-ai-toward-self-learning-with-seal-framework/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about SEAL:\n\n## SEAL: Self-Adapting Language Models\n\nIn mid-2025, researchers at MIT's Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory (CSAIL) unveiled a groundbreaking technique called SEAL—short for Self-Adapting Language Models.\n\n### How It Works\n\nThis framework enables large language models (LLMs) to autonomously improve themselves by generating and applying their own fine-tuning data. Rather than relying on external retraining or human-curated datasets, SEAL allows models to produce structured \"self-edits\" that include synthetic training examples, optimization instructions, and even gradient-based update directives.\n\nSEAL breaks this constraint by introducing a two-loop system: an inner loop where the model generates its own self-edit in response to new input, and an outer loop where that self-edit is used to fine-tune the model.\n\n### Key Advantages\n\nTraditional LLMs are static once deployed, unable to internalize new knowledge or adapt to novel tasks without manual intervention. SEAL addresses this by using self-edits in supervised fine-tuning, resulting in persistent updates to the model's weights and capabilities.\n\n### Performance Results\n\nOn question answering, SEAL improved model accuracy by nearly 15% and on some skill-learning tasks, it boosted the success rate by more than 50%. Additionally, in few-shot learning tasks, the success rate jumped to 72.5%, up from 20% using self-edits generated without reinforcement learning."],"durationSeconds":8.949633916000137,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"f3efb491-4396-4c16-838d-90fbc87cc5b1","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"a6f11d48-417e-4372-8d9b-e79126dc40cb","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JRPhS1Di4VhRdw2fiEXeno","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"self-improving LLM agent prompt optimization OPRO EvoPrompt PromptBreeder STOP Self-Taught Optimizer guardrails\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"A Survey of Self-Evolving Agents: What, When, How, and Where to Evolve on the Path to Artificial Super Intelligence\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.21046\"},{\"title\":\"PMPO: Probabilistic Metric Prompt Optimization for Small and Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.16307\"},{\"title\":\"Automatic Prompt Optimization - by Cameron R. Wolfe, Ph.D.\",\"url\":\"https://cameronrwolfe.substack.com/p/automatic-prompt-optimization\"},{\"title\":\"SI-Agent: An Agentic Framework for Feedback-Driven Generation and Tuning of Human-Readable System Instructions for Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.03223\"},{\"title\":\"SEE: Strategic Exploration and Exploitation for Cohesive In-Context Prompt Optimization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.11347\"},{\"title\":\"Promptbreeder: Self-Referential Self-Improvement via Prompt Evolution | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HKkiX32Zw1\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Improvement of Large Language Models: A Technical Overview and Future Outlook\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.25681\"},{\"title\":\"A Comprehensive Survey of Self-Evolving AI Agents: A New Paradigm Bridging Foundation Models and Lifelong Agentic Systems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.07407\"},{\"title\":\"Efficient Prompting Methods for Large Language Models: A Survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2404.01077v2\"},{\"title\":\"self-referential self-improvement via prompt evolution\",\"url\":\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.5555/3692070.3692611\"}]\n\nNow let me search for information about STOP Self-Taught Optimizer and guardrails:\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2310.02304\"},{\"title\":\"Trace is the Next AutoDiff: Generative Optimization with Rich Feedback,   Execution Traces, and LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.16218\"},{\"title\":\"1 Illustration of the use-case of a guardrail model for LLMs, which functions as moderation between the user-LLM conversation.\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.05163\"},{\"title\":\"A Survey on LLM Guardrails: Part 1, Methods, Best Practices and Optimisations - BudEcosystem\",\"url\":\"https://blog.budecosystem.com/a-survey-on-llm-guardrails-methods-best-practices-and-optimisations/\"},{\"title\":\"SelfGrader: Stable Jailbreak Detection for Large Language Models using Token-Level Logits\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.01473\"},{\"title\":\"Auto-Tuning Safety Guardrails for Black-Box Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.15782\"},{\"title\":\"LLM Guardrails for Data Leakage, Prompt Injection, and More - Confident AI\",\"url\":\"https://www.confident-ai.com/blog/llm-guardrails-the-ultimate-guide-to-safeguard-llm-systems\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, here's a comprehensive overview of self-improving LLM agents and prompt optimization techniques:\n\n## Prompt Optimization Approaches\n\nPrompt Optimization (PO) enables LLM agents to self-evolve by refining the instructions it feeds to the backbone model, which directly alters the model's behavior without modifying model weights.\n\nSeveral key techniques have emerged:\n\n**OPRO**: OPRO treats prompt design as a black-box optimization problem where an LLM iteratively proposes and evaluates new prompts based on previous ones and their accuracy on training examples.\n\n**EvoPrompt**: EvoPrompt combines evolutionary algorithms with LLMs to maintain and evolve a population of prompts through mutation and selection, with new prompts generated via LLM-guided variation and top-performing variants retained across generations.\n\n**PromptBreeder**: PromptBreeder evolves both task prompts and mutation strategies in parallel, using co-evolution to generate increasingly effective prompts without human intervention and achieving state-of-the-art performance on complex reasoning benchmarks. The key distinction is that Promptbreeder optimizes more than just the task prompt—the prompt used to implement evolutionary operators is optimized as well, introducing a self-improvement mechanism within the prompt optimization algorithm itself.\n\n## Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP)\n\nSTOP is a framework for recursively optimizing code generation using LMs as meta-optimizers, demonstrating that LMs like GPT-4 are capable of improving code that leverages the LM itself and generating improvers that boost the performance of downstream code. STOP does not alter the black-box LM and is not full recursive self-improvement, and the scaffolding systems it creates are not currently superior to those hand-engineered by experts.\n\nNotably, STOP facilitates the study of aspects of recursive self-improvement in code generation such as sandbox avoidance and reward hacking.\n\n## Guardrails for LLMs\n\nLLM guardrails are pre-defined rules and filters designed to protect LLM applications from vulnerabilities like data leakage, bias, and hallucination, and shield against malicious inputs such as prompt injections and jailbreaking attempts. Safety is implemented through deployment-time guardrails such as system prompts, safety policies, and content filters wrapped around a frozen base model, and simple changes to system prompts, refusal templates, or classifier thresholds can significantly alter an application's vulnerability.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"cbb079a3-6e63-4b21-aa26-30752ff510b7","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:20.946Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"self-improving LLM agent prompt optimization OPRO EvoPrompt PromptBreeder STOP Self-Taught Optimizer guardrails","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012jyefKfegosQMzytm6s4aY","content":[{"title":"A Survey of Self-Evolving Agents: What, When, How, and Where to Evolve on the Path to Artificial Super Intelligence","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.21046"},{"title":"PMPO: Probabilistic Metric Prompt Optimization for Small and Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.16307"},{"title":"Automatic Prompt Optimization - by Cameron R. Wolfe, Ph.D.","url":"https://cameronrwolfe.substack.com/p/automatic-prompt-optimization"},{"title":"SI-Agent: An Agentic Framework for Feedback-Driven Generation and Tuning of Human-Readable System Instructions for Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.03223"},{"title":"SEE: Strategic Exploration and Exploitation for Cohesive In-Context Prompt Optimization","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.11347"},{"title":"Promptbreeder: Self-Referential Self-Improvement via Prompt Evolution | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HKkiX32Zw1"},{"title":"Self-Improvement of Large Language Models: A Technical Overview and Future Outlook","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.25681"},{"title":"A Comprehensive Survey of Self-Evolving AI Agents: A New Paradigm Bridging Foundation Models and Lifelong Agentic Systems","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.07407"},{"title":"Efficient Prompting Methods for Large Language Models: A Survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2404.01077v2"},{"title":"self-referential self-improvement via prompt evolution","url":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.5555/3692070.3692611"}]},"Now let me search for information about STOP Self-Taught Optimizer and guardrails:",{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01AjW2C743u4UjYpVghbw3UN","content":[{"title":"Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP): Recursively Self-Improving Code Generation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2310.02304"},{"title":"Trace is the Next AutoDiff: Generative Optimization with Rich Feedback,   Execution Traces, and LLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.16218"},{"title":"1 Illustration of the use-case of a guardrail model for LLMs, which functions as moderation between the user-LLM conversation.","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.05163"},{"title":"A Survey on LLM Guardrails: Part 1, Methods, Best Practices and Optimisations - BudEcosystem","url":"https://blog.budecosystem.com/a-survey-on-llm-guardrails-methods-best-practices-and-optimisations/"},{"title":"SelfGrader: Stable Jailbreak Detection for Large Language Models using Token-Level Logits","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.01473"},{"title":"Auto-Tuning Safety Guardrails for Black-Box Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.15782"},{"title":"LLM Guardrails for Data Leakage, Prompt Injection, and More - Confident AI","url":"https://www.confident-ai.com/blog/llm-guardrails-the-ultimate-guide-to-safeguard-llm-systems"}]},"Based on the web search results, here's a comprehensive overview of self-improving LLM agents and prompt optimization techniques:\n\n## Prompt Optimization Approaches\n\nPrompt Optimization (PO) enables LLM agents to self-evolve by refining the instructions it feeds to the backbone model, which directly alters the model's behavior without modifying model weights.\n\nSeveral key techniques have emerged:\n\n**OPRO**: OPRO treats prompt design as a black-box optimization problem where an LLM iteratively proposes and evaluates new prompts based on previous ones and their accuracy on training examples.\n\n**EvoPrompt**: EvoPrompt combines evolutionary algorithms with LLMs to maintain and evolve a population of prompts through mutation and selection, with new prompts generated via LLM-guided variation and top-performing variants retained across generations.\n\n**PromptBreeder**: PromptBreeder evolves both task prompts and mutation strategies in parallel, using co-evolution to generate increasingly effective prompts without human intervention and achieving state-of-the-art performance on complex reasoning benchmarks. The key distinction is that Promptbreeder optimizes more than just the task prompt—the prompt used to implement evolutionary operators is optimized as well, introducing a self-improvement mechanism within the prompt optimization algorithm itself.\n\n## Self-Taught Optimizer (STOP)\n\nSTOP is a framework for recursively optimizing code generation using LMs as meta-optimizers, demonstrating that LMs like GPT-4 are capable of improving code that leverages the LM itself and generating improvers that boost the performance of downstream code. STOP does not alter the black-box LM and is not full recursive self-improvement, and the scaffolding systems it creates are not currently superior to those hand-engineered by experts.\n\nNotably, STOP facilitates the study of aspects of recursive self-improvement in code generation such as sandbox avoidance and reward hacking.\n\n## Guardrails for LLMs\n\nLLM guardrails are pre-defined rules and filters designed to protect LLM applications from vulnerabilities like data leakage, bias, and hallucination, and shield against malicious inputs such as prompt injections and jailbreaking attempts. Safety is implemented through deployment-time guardrails such as system prompts, safety policies, and content filters wrapped around a frozen base model, and simple changes to system prompts, refusal templates, or classifier thresholds can significantly alter an application's vulnerability."],"durationSeconds":14.704234916999937,"searchCount":2},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a6f11d48-417e-4372-8d9b-e79126dc40cb","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
