{"parentUuid":"b6c1a261-b9e9-48fe-a52c-afbec320d7ae","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MwRAVnckkADPaRoESJvoFr","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"statistical significance small sample A/B test accept improvement over noise sequential testing regression detection benchmark pass rate\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"What is statistical significance in A/B testing? - Q&A - Nicola Lazzari\",\"url\":\"https://nicolalazzari.ai/q/what-is-statistical-significance-in-ab-testing\"},{\"title\":\"Simple Sequential A/B Testing – Evan Miller\",\"url\":\"https://www.evanmiller.org/sequential-ab-testing.html\"},{\"title\":\"Statistical Significance in A/B Testing – a Complete Guide | Analytics-Toolkit.com\",\"url\":\"https://blog.analytics-toolkit.com/2017/statistical-significance-ab-testing-complete-guide/\"},{\"title\":\"Sequential testing: How to peek at A/B test results without ruining validity\",\"url\":\"https://www.statsig.com/perspectives/sequential-testing-ab-peek\"},{\"title\":\"A/B Testing with a Small Sample Size | Analytics-Toolkit.com\",\"url\":\"https://blog.analytics-toolkit.com/2019/a-b-testing-with-a-small-sample-size/\"},{\"title\":\"Sample size calculator - Optimizely\",\"url\":\"https://www.optimizely.com/sample-size-calculator/\"},{\"title\":\"Sequential testing for statistical inference | Amplitude Experiment\",\"url\":\"https://amplitude.com/docs/feature-experiment/under-the-hood/experiment-sequential-testing\"},{\"title\":\"What is sequential testing? (with examples) - Eppo\",\"url\":\"https://www.geteppo.com/blog/sequential-testing\"},{\"title\":\"Sequential Test for Practical Significance: Truncated Mixture Sequential Probability Ratio Test\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.07892\"}]\n\nHere are the web search results for your query about statistical significance, small sample A/B tests, sequential testing, and related concepts:\n\n## Key Findings\n\n**Sequential Testing for Small Samples:**\n\nSequential testing excels at quickly identifying small lifts in low-conversion settings and allows winning tests to be stopped early without committing the statistical sin of repeated significance testing. Using sequential testing statistics can result in 20%-80% faster tests, meaning that a sequential test would, on average, require 20% to 80% fewer users compared to an equivalent fixed-sample size test.\n\n**How Sequential Testing Works:**\n\nSequential testing uses statistical adjustments that essentially raise the bar for significance as you check more often. Sequential testing refers to any procedure in which, after each observation, exactly one of the following decisions is made: accept the null hypothesis, reject the null hypothesis, or collect an additional observation.\n\n**Trade-offs:**\n\nSequential testing involves trading some statistical power for the ability to make faster decisions, and if you don't find significance early, you might have a harder time detecting smaller effects later.\n\n**Statistical Significance Standards:**\n\nStandard thresholds for statistical significance are p < 0.05 (5% - 95% confidence the result is real) or p < 0.01 (1% - 99% sure the result is real for high-stakes decisions).\n\nThe search results emphasize that small sample sizes make it harder to detect real differences, but sequential testing methods can help mitigate this challenge.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"be3780a3-e5b6-4eff-9582-c6cbaaa2aacd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:32.414Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"statistical significance small sample A/B test accept improvement over noise sequential testing regression detection benchmark pass rate","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01DnTAp1UKr4ohYzCbZXPvXH","content":[{"title":"What is statistical significance in A/B testing? - Q&A - Nicola Lazzari","url":"https://nicolalazzari.ai/q/what-is-statistical-significance-in-ab-testing"},{"title":"Simple Sequential A/B Testing – Evan Miller","url":"https://www.evanmiller.org/sequential-ab-testing.html"},{"title":"Statistical Significance in A/B Testing – a Complete Guide | Analytics-Toolkit.com","url":"https://blog.analytics-toolkit.com/2017/statistical-significance-ab-testing-complete-guide/"},{"title":"Sequential testing: How to peek at A/B test results without ruining validity","url":"https://www.statsig.com/perspectives/sequential-testing-ab-peek"},{"title":"A/B Testing with a Small Sample Size | Analytics-Toolkit.com","url":"https://blog.analytics-toolkit.com/2019/a-b-testing-with-a-small-sample-size/"},{"title":"Sample size calculator - Optimizely","url":"https://www.optimizely.com/sample-size-calculator/"},{"title":"Sequential testing for statistical inference | Amplitude Experiment","url":"https://amplitude.com/docs/feature-experiment/under-the-hood/experiment-sequential-testing"},{"title":"What is sequential testing? (with examples) - Eppo","url":"https://www.geteppo.com/blog/sequential-testing"},{"title":"Sequential Test for Practical Significance: Truncated Mixture Sequential Probability Ratio Test","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.07892"}]},"Here are the web search results for your query about statistical significance, small sample A/B tests, sequential testing, and related concepts:\n\n## Key Findings\n\n**Sequential Testing for Small Samples:**\n\nSequential testing excels at quickly identifying small lifts in low-conversion settings and allows winning tests to be stopped early without committing the statistical sin of repeated significance testing. Using sequential testing statistics can result in 20%-80% faster tests, meaning that a sequential test would, on average, require 20% to 80% fewer users compared to an equivalent fixed-sample size test.\n\n**How Sequential Testing Works:**\n\nSequential testing uses statistical adjustments that essentially raise the bar for significance as you check more often. Sequential testing refers to any procedure in which, after each observation, exactly one of the following decisions is made: accept the null hypothesis, reject the null hypothesis, or collect an additional observation.\n\n**Trade-offs:**\n\nSequential testing involves trading some statistical power for the ability to make faster decisions, and if you don't find significance early, you might have a harder time detecting smaller effects later.\n\n**Statistical Significance Standards:**\n\nStandard thresholds for statistical significance are p < 0.05 (5% - 95% confidence the result is real) or p < 0.01 (1% - 99% sure the result is real for high-stakes decisions).\n\nThe search results emphasize that small sample sizes make it harder to detect real differences, but sequential testing methods can help mitigate this challenge."],"durationSeconds":7.592751084000105,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b6c1a261-b9e9-48fe-a52c-afbec320d7ae","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"63457a81-168c-4100-a968-93ed3b75373f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01183fpmDZHz4jCY7g2UfEDj","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"VC dimension capacity bound self-modifying learning system learnability under self-modification utility tension\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"On The Statistical Limits of Self-Improving Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.04399\"},{\"title\":\"1 Introduction\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.04399v2\"},{\"title\":\"Computational Learning Theory 3 : VC Dimension Lecturer: Varun Kanade\",\"url\":\"https://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/people/varun.kanade/teaching/CLT-MT2018/lectures/lecture03.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Learnability and VC Dimension | 6.790 Machine Learning\",\"url\":\"https://gradml.mit.edu/supervised/learnability_and_vc/\"},{\"title\":\"4. Learnability and VC Dimension 4.1. PAC framework\",\"url\":\"https://www.mathematik.uni-muenchen.de/~deckert/teaching/SS17/ATML/media/VC_dimension.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Why Code, Why Now: An Information-Theoretic Perspective on the Limits of Machine Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.13934\"},{\"title\":\"Learning Complexity Dimensions for a Continuous-Time Control System\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0012163\"},{\"title\":\"Vapnik-Chervonenkis Dimension - GeeksforGeeks\",\"url\":\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension/\"},{\"title\":\"The Dimension of Self-Directed Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.13400\"}]\n\nThe search has returned highly relevant results. The first source appears to be a research paper directly addressing your query. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Key Results\n\nA sharp learnability boundary for self-modifying agents has been established: distribution-free PAC guarantees are preserved if and only if the policy-reachable hypothesis family has uniformly bounded capacity.\n\nThis result unifies representational, architectural, algorithmic, metacognitive, and substrate modifications under a single criterion: the supremum VC dimension of states reachable under the agent's utility function.\n\n## The Utility Tension\n\nThe research reveals a fundamental tension in self-modifying systems: seemingly rational self-modifications can irreversibly destroy learnability when capacity grows without bound, even as they improve immediate performance.\n\n## Practical Approach\n\nThe Two-Gate policy provides a computable guardrail that enforces this boundary through validation margins and capacity caps, yielding oracle inequalities at standard VC rates.\n\n## Broader Implications\n\nFuture self-modifying systems should ask not what maximizes validation accuracy, but what maximizes accuracy subject to capacity remaining PAC learnable for available data. For open-ended agents operating over long horizons, the capacity schedule can grow with accumulating data, enabling unbounded absolute improvement while maintaining learnability.\n\nThis research appears to be from a paper titled \"On The Statistical Limits of Self-Improving Agents\" (arxiv.org/pdf/2510.04399), published in February 2026.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"5a9997df-b685-4088-95a2-8d412b76556c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:34.103Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"VC dimension capacity bound self-modifying learning system learnability under self-modification utility tension","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01YDacKErP14BfFhy9S6etmY","content":[{"title":"On The Statistical Limits of Self-Improving Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.04399"},{"title":"1 Introduction","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.04399v2"},{"title":"Computational Learning Theory 3 : VC Dimension Lecturer: Varun Kanade","url":"https://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/people/varun.kanade/teaching/CLT-MT2018/lectures/lecture03.pdf"},{"title":"Learnability and VC Dimension | 6.790 Machine Learning","url":"https://gradml.mit.edu/supervised/learnability_and_vc/"},{"title":"4. Learnability and VC Dimension 4.1. PAC framework","url":"https://www.mathematik.uni-muenchen.de/~deckert/teaching/SS17/ATML/media/VC_dimension.pdf"},{"title":"Why Code, Why Now: An Information-Theoretic Perspective on the Limits of Machine Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.13934"},{"title":"Learning Complexity Dimensions for a Continuous-Time Control System","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0012163"},{"title":"Vapnik-Chervonenkis Dimension - GeeksforGeeks","url":"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/vapnik-chervonenkis-dimension/"},{"title":"The Dimension of Self-Directed Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.13400"}]},"The search has returned highly relevant results. The first source appears to be a research paper directly addressing your query. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Key Results\n\nA sharp learnability boundary for self-modifying agents has been established: distribution-free PAC guarantees are preserved if and only if the policy-reachable hypothesis family has uniformly bounded capacity.\n\nThis result unifies representational, architectural, algorithmic, metacognitive, and substrate modifications under a single criterion: the supremum VC dimension of states reachable under the agent's utility function.\n\n## The Utility Tension\n\nThe research reveals a fundamental tension in self-modifying systems: seemingly rational self-modifications can irreversibly destroy learnability when capacity grows without bound, even as they improve immediate performance.\n\n## Practical Approach\n\nThe Two-Gate policy provides a computable guardrail that enforces this boundary through validation margins and capacity caps, yielding oracle inequalities at standard VC rates.\n\n## Broader Implications\n\nFuture self-modifying systems should ask not what maximizes validation accuracy, but what maximizes accuracy subject to capacity remaining PAC learnable for available data. For open-ended agents operating over long horizons, the capacity schedule can grow with accumulating data, enabling unbounded absolute improvement while maintaining learnability.\n\nThis research appears to be from a paper titled \"On The Statistical Limits of Self-Improving Agents\" (arxiv.org/pdf/2510.04399), published in February 2026."],"durationSeconds":8.453447999999858,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"63457a81-168c-4100-a968-93ed3b75373f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"5b9dfe77-583a-4d0c-acbc-9523955462f4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013Y4YSSDgfz2j1PCGkVyLon","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LLM self-evaluation bias self-preference inflated scores LLM judge mitigation separate evaluator calibration 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Self-Preference Bias in Rubric-Based Evaluation of Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.06996\"},{\"title\":\"LLM-Judge Bias Mitigation (2026): Detect, Measure, Fix\",\"url\":\"https://futureagi.com/blog/evaluating-llm-judge-bias-mitigation-2026/\"},{\"title\":\"LLM-as-a-Judge Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/llm-as-a-judge-evaluations\"},{\"title\":\"LLM-as-a-Judge vs Human Evaluation\",\"url\":\"https://galileo.ai/blog/llm-as-a-judge-vs-human-evaluation\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Self-Preference Bias in LLM-as-a-Judge\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/385353198_Self-Preference_Bias_in_LLM-as-a-Judge\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Preference Bias in LLM-as-a-Judge\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.21819v2\"},{\"title\":\"Evaluating Scoring Bias in LLM-as-a-Judge\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.22316v1\"},{\"title\":\"BEYOND CONSENSUS: MITIGATING THE AGREEABLE- NESS BIAS IN LLM JUDGE EVALUATIONS\",\"url\":\"https://aicet.comp.nus.edu.sg/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Beyond-Consensus-Mitigating-the-agreeableness-bias-in-LLM-judge-evaluations.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Do LLM Evaluators Prefer Themselves for a Reason?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.03846\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, here's what recent research reveals about LLM self-evaluation bias and mitigation strategies:\n\n## Self-Preference Bias Overview\n\nSelf-preference bias in LLM evaluators has attracted growing attention from numerous recent studies (2023-2025). A judge scores outputs from its own model family 10 to 25 percent higher than equivalent outputs from a different family.\n\n## Key Findings on the Bias\n\nResearch shows self-preference bias in pairwise comparison is correlated with the judge's ability to identify its own outputs. More specifically, researchers propose the Harmful Self-Preference Propensity metric, which restricts analysis to cases where the judge's own output is objectively worse, and find that even in these cases judges tend to favor themselves.\n\nStudies have discovered a linear correlation between self-recognition capability and the strength of self-preference bias of LLM evaluators.\n\n## Mitigation Strategies\n\nSeveral approaches have been proposed to address this bias:\n\n1. **Cross-family Judging**: Using judges from different model families than the generators mitigates this bias.\n\n2. **Position and Score Calibration**: Researchers propose methods to calibrate positional bias in LLM-as-a-Judge, including multiple evidence calibration, balanced position calibration, and human-in-the-loop calibration.\n\n3. **Position Swapping**: To mitigate bias, researchers swap the positions of responses and average evaluation scores over multiple iterations.\n\n4. **Comprehensive Framework**: The Autorubric framework supports mitigations for position bias (option shuffling), verbosity bias (length penalties), and criterion conflation.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"45c72944-cd32-4068-8826-5af4f97865e4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:34.884Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"LLM self-evaluation bias self-preference inflated scores LLM judge mitigation separate evaluator calibration 2024 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01V4biSzP8KbPyJUs4qeqPRS","content":[{"title":"Self-Preference Bias in Rubric-Based Evaluation of Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.06996"},{"title":"LLM-Judge Bias Mitigation (2026): Detect, Measure, Fix","url":"https://futureagi.com/blog/evaluating-llm-judge-bias-mitigation-2026/"},{"title":"LLM-as-a-Judge Evaluation","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/llm-as-a-judge-evaluations"},{"title":"LLM-as-a-Judge vs Human Evaluation","url":"https://galileo.ai/blog/llm-as-a-judge-vs-human-evaluation"},{"title":"(PDF) Self-Preference Bias in LLM-as-a-Judge","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/385353198_Self-Preference_Bias_in_LLM-as-a-Judge"},{"title":"Self-Preference Bias in LLM-as-a-Judge","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.21819v2"},{"title":"Evaluating Scoring Bias in LLM-as-a-Judge","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.22316v1"},{"title":"BEYOND CONSENSUS: MITIGATING THE AGREEABLE- NESS BIAS IN LLM JUDGE EVALUATIONS","url":"https://aicet.comp.nus.edu.sg/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/Beyond-Consensus-Mitigating-the-agreeableness-bias-in-LLM-judge-evaluations.pdf"},{"title":"Do LLM Evaluators Prefer Themselves for a Reason?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.03846"}]},"Based on the web search results, here's what recent research reveals about LLM self-evaluation bias and mitigation strategies:\n\n## Self-Preference Bias Overview\n\nSelf-preference bias in LLM evaluators has attracted growing attention from numerous recent studies (2023-2025). A judge scores outputs from its own model family 10 to 25 percent higher than equivalent outputs from a different family.\n\n## Key Findings on the Bias\n\nResearch shows self-preference bias in pairwise comparison is correlated with the judge's ability to identify its own outputs. More specifically, researchers propose the Harmful Self-Preference Propensity metric, which restricts analysis to cases where the judge's own output is objectively worse, and find that even in these cases judges tend to favor themselves.\n\nStudies have discovered a linear correlation between self-recognition capability and the strength of self-preference bias of LLM evaluators.\n\n## Mitigation Strategies\n\nSeveral approaches have been proposed to address this bias:\n\n1. **Cross-family Judging**: Using judges from different model families than the generators mitigates this bias.\n\n2. **Position and Score Calibration**: Researchers propose methods to calibrate positional bias in LLM-as-a-Judge, including multiple evidence calibration, balanced position calibration, and human-in-the-loop calibration.\n\n3. **Position Swapping**: To mitigate bias, researchers swap the positions of responses and average evaluation scores over multiple iterations.\n\n4. **Comprehensive Framework**: The Autorubric framework supports mitigations for position bias (option shuffling), verbosity bias (length penalties), and criterion conflation."],"durationSeconds":8.772961750000016,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5b9dfe77-583a-4d0c-acbc-9523955462f4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"4fc36782-d6db-4a3d-bee4-99b9c407fbd9","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01F16UudrQ1eMuzJJ4xEqf48","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Gödel Agent recursive self-improvement framework arxiv guardrails\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2410.04444v1] Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement\",\"url\":\"http://arxiv.org/abs/2410.04444v1\"},{\"title\":\"Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursively Self-Improvement\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.04444v4\"},{\"title\":\"[2410.04444v2] Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.04444v2\"},{\"title\":\"[2410.04444] Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.04444\"},{\"title\":\"Godel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement | AI Research Paper Details\",\"url\":\"https://www.aimodels.fyi/papers/arxiv/godel-agent-self-referential-agent-framework-recursive\"},{\"title\":\"Gödel Agent for Recursive Self-Improvement: A Comprehensive Tutorial · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://gist.github.com/ruvnet/15c6ef556be49e173ab0ecd6d252a7b9\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - Arvid-pku/Godel_Agent: Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/Arvid-pku/Godel_Agent\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about the Gödel Agent recursive self-improvement framework:\n\n## Overview\n\nGödel Agent is a self-evolving framework inspired by the Gödel machine, enabling agents to recursively improve themselves without relying on predefined routines or fixed optimization algorithms. Gödel Agent leverages LLMs to dynamically modify its own logic and behavior, guided solely by high-level objectives through prompting.\n\n## Key Capabilities\n\nGödel Agent can analyze and modify its own code, including the code for analyzing and modifying itself, and thus can search the full agent design space. It autonomously engages in self-awareness, self-modification, and recursive self-improvement.\n\n## Problem It Addresses\n\nExisting agentic systems cannot search the whole agent design space due to the restriction of human-designed components, and thus might miss the globally optimal agent design.\n\n## Results\n\nExperimental results on mathematical reasoning and complex agent tasks demonstrate that implementation of Gödel Agent can achieve continuous self-improvement, surpassing manually crafted agents in performance, efficiency, and generalization.\n\nThe paper appears to have been published on arXiv in October 2024 (arxiv:2410.04444) by Xunjian Yin, Xinyi Wang, Liangming Pan, Xiaojun Wan, and William Yang Wang. However, the search results do not contain specific information about guardrails implementation in the framework.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"eaf28555-b34a-4949-abf0-b5540be0698f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:39.468Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Gödel Agent recursive self-improvement framework arxiv guardrails","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01TfuSKqTsZuTN7rjLRUcf8d","content":[{"title":"[2410.04444v1] Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement","url":"http://arxiv.org/abs/2410.04444v1"},{"title":"Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursively Self-Improvement","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.04444v4"},{"title":"[2410.04444v2] Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.04444v2"},{"title":"[2410.04444] Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.04444"},{"title":"Godel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement | AI Research Paper Details","url":"https://www.aimodels.fyi/papers/arxiv/godel-agent-self-referential-agent-framework-recursive"},{"title":"Gödel Agent for Recursive Self-Improvement: A Comprehensive Tutorial · GitHub","url":"https://gist.github.com/ruvnet/15c6ef556be49e173ab0ecd6d252a7b9"},{"title":"GitHub - Arvid-pku/Godel_Agent: Gödel Agent: A Self-Referential Agent Framework for Recursive Self-Improvement · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/Arvid-pku/Godel_Agent"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about the Gödel Agent recursive self-improvement framework:\n\n## Overview\n\nGödel Agent is a self-evolving framework inspired by the Gödel machine, enabling agents to recursively improve themselves without relying on predefined routines or fixed optimization algorithms. Gödel Agent leverages LLMs to dynamically modify its own logic and behavior, guided solely by high-level objectives through prompting.\n\n## Key Capabilities\n\nGödel Agent can analyze and modify its own code, including the code for analyzing and modifying itself, and thus can search the full agent design space. It autonomously engages in self-awareness, self-modification, and recursive self-improvement.\n\n## Problem It Addresses\n\nExisting agentic systems cannot search the whole agent design space due to the restriction of human-designed components, and thus might miss the globally optimal agent design.\n\n## Results\n\nExperimental results on mathematical reasoning and complex agent tasks demonstrate that implementation of Gödel Agent can achieve continuous self-improvement, surpassing manually crafted agents in performance, efficiency, and generalization.\n\nThe paper appears to have been published on arXiv in October 2024 (arxiv:2410.04444) by Xunjian Yin, Xinyi Wang, Liangming Pan, Xiaojun Wan, and William Yang Wang. However, the search results do not contain specific information about guardrails implementation in the framework."],"durationSeconds":12.810776084000011,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4fc36782-d6db-4a3d-bee4-99b9c407fbd9","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
