{"parentUuid":"b94a7ed1-021c-4083-8471-8e1b338f0339","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Jx3qeiwFf3D38zNJLkez2H","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01NxnzquSoEbmueXUuWFKFpT","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.04399v2","prompt":"Extract the precise definitions and operational details of: (1) the Two-Gate policy — the Validation Gate (validation margin) and the Capacity Gate (capacity cap). How is the validation margin computed and what threshold relative to noise is used to accept a self-edit? (2) How is capacity / VC dimension bounded operationally — what is the capacity cap, and how does it relate to policy-reachable hypothesis families? (3) The utility-learnability tension theorem. (4) Any oracle inequality / VC-rate guarantees. (5) Practical proxies for capacity when editing prompts/policies rather than weights. (6) The capacity schedule that grows with data. Quote formulas and thresholds where given."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8826,"cache_read_input_tokens":16276,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":8826,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFksUxBCDb5wA7fcRfLi","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"b667c2c0-90af-4e86-836e-43a75793e709","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:47.449Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b667c2c0-90af-4e86-836e-43a75793e709","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Jx3qeiwFf3D38zNJLkez2H","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Kw6SjNrjmmWr9CJKspBXs7","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.26354","prompt":"Extract: the four misevolution pathways (model, memory, tool, workflow) and the specific failure modes/empirical numbers for each. What mitigations or safety recommendations does the paper propose against misevolution? What does it say about reward/objective hacking and safety degradation over evolutionary cycles?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8826,"cache_read_input_tokens":16276,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":8826,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFksUxBCDb5wA7fcRfLi","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"c22cdd8b-afae-4e3b-b0b2-e35476c55e1b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:49.135Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"c22cdd8b-afae-4e3b-b0b2-e35476c55e1b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kw6SjNrjmmWr9CJKspBXs7","type":"tool_result","content":"# Analysis of Misevolution in Self-Evolving LLM Agents\n\n## Four Evolutionary Pathways\n\nThe paper evaluates misevolution across four dimensions:\n- **Model**: Self-improvement through model updates\n- **Memory**: Learning from accumulated interaction history\n- **Tool**: Development and integration of new capabilities\n- **Workflow**: Evolution of agent process and strategy\n\nHowever, the provided abstract does not include specific empirical numbers or failure modes for each pathway.\n\n## Key Failure Modes Identified\n\nThe abstract mentions two specific emergent risks:\n\n1. **Safety Alignment Degradation**: \"degradation of safety alignment after memory accumulation\"\n2. **Tool Vulnerabilities**: \"unintended introduction of vulnerabilities in tool creation and reuse\"\n\nThe research demonstrates that misevolution affects agents \"even on top-tier LLMs (e.g., Gemini-2.5-Pro).\"\n\n## Proposed Mitigations\n\nThe abstract indicates the paper \"discusses potential mitigation strategies to inspire further research on building safer and more trustworthy self-evolving agents,\" but specific recommendations are not detailed in the available content.\n\n## Reward Hacking and Safety Degradation\n\nThe abstract does not explicitly address reward/objective hacking or provide detailed analysis of safety degradation across evolutionary cycles—these topics may be covered in the full paper available via PDF.\n\n**Note**: For complete details on empirical results, specific failure rates, and mitigation strategies, access to the full paper is necessary."}]},"uuid":"37d32415-f3a8-4e29-a2fd-8c66cef0cc38","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:15:54.021Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":48355,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Analysis of Misevolution in Self-Evolving LLM Agents\n\n## Four Evolutionary Pathways\n\nThe paper evaluates misevolution across four dimensions:\n- **Model**: Self-improvement through model updates\n- **Memory**: Learning from accumulated interaction history\n- **Tool**: Development and integration of new capabilities\n- **Workflow**: Evolution of agent process and strategy\n\nHowever, the provided abstract does not include specific empirical numbers or failure modes for each pathway.\n\n## Key Failure Modes Identified\n\nThe abstract mentions two specific emergent risks:\n\n1. **Safety Alignment Degradation**: \"degradation of safety alignment after memory accumulation\"\n2. **Tool Vulnerabilities**: \"unintended introduction of vulnerabilities in tool creation and reuse\"\n\nThe research demonstrates that misevolution affects agents \"even on top-tier LLMs (e.g., Gemini-2.5-Pro).\"\n\n## Proposed Mitigations\n\nThe abstract indicates the paper \"discusses potential mitigation strategies to inspire further research on building safer and more trustworthy self-evolving agents,\" but specific recommendations are not detailed in the available content.\n\n## Reward Hacking and Safety Degradation\n\nThe abstract does not explicitly address reward/objective hacking or provide detailed analysis of safety degradation across evolutionary cycles—these topics may be covered in the full paper available via PDF.\n\n**Note**: For complete details on empirical results, specific failure rates, and mitigation strategies, access to the full paper is necessary.","durationMs":4719,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.26354"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c22cdd8b-afae-4e3b-b0b2-e35476c55e1b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b667c2c0-90af-4e86-836e-43a75793e709","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"fb0cadc7-1603-40bf-9d82-d900b7efd84a","agentId":"a8a9cbb753123834b","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NxnzquSoEbmueXUuWFKFpT","type":"tool_result","content":"# Two-Gate Policy and Capacity-Bounded Self-Modification\n\n## (1) Two-Gate Policy: Validation and Capacity Gates\n\n**Validation Gate (Validation Margin):**\nAn edit is accepted only if:\n```\nR̂_V[h_new] ≤ R̂_V[h_old] − [2ε_V + τ]\n```\n\nwhere ε_V satisfies:\n```\nsup_{h ∈ G_K[m]} |R[h] − R̂_V[h]| ≤ ε_V\n```\n\nwith probability ≥ 1 − δ_V over validation samples. The paper specifies that \"ε_V ≍ √[(K[m] + log(1/δ_V))/n_v]\" by classical VC uniform convergence bounds.\n\nThe margin τ ≥ 0 is user-specified; each accepted edit must reduce empirical validation risk by at least the noise floor plus the stability margin.\n\n**Capacity Gate (Capacity Cap):**\n```\nh_new ∈ G_K[m]  and  VC[G_K[m]] ≤ K[m]\n```\n\nThe capped reference family G_K[m] is fixed before observing validation data. Only edits producing hypotheses within this family are permitted.\n\n---\n\n## (2) Operational Capacity Bounding\n\n**Capacity Cap Schedule K[m]:**\nThe paper defines K[·] as a \"nondecreasing capacity cap schedule at sample size m.\" The schedule grows with available training data, enabling \"unbounded absolute improvement while maintaining learnability.\"\n\n**Proxy-Based Enforcement (Architectural Case):**\nFor systems where true VC dimension is intractable, a computable upper-bound proxy B[Z] replaces direct VC measurement:\n```\nVC[H[Z]] ≤ B[Z]  for all Z ∈ Z\n```\n\nThe proxy-capped subfamily is then:\n```\nG^proxy_K = {h ∈ G: ∃Z with B[Z] ≤ K and h ∈ H[Z]}\n```\n\nOnly edits satisfying B[Z_new] ≤ K[m] are accepted.\n\n---\n\n## (3) Utility-Learnability Tension (Core Theorem 1)\n\n**Statement:**\n\"Distribution-free PAC learnability is preserved under representational self-modification if and only if sup_{H' ∈ H_reach[u]} VC[H'] < ∞.\"\n\n**Tension Mechanism:**\nUtilities that reward empirical fit and capacity growth can drive policy-reachable VC unbounded. The paper proves: \"when capacity can grow without limit, utility-rational self-changes can render learnable tasks unlearnable.\" Even local capacity increases compounding across iterations destroy distribution-free guarantees.\n\n---\n\n## (4) Oracle Inequality and VC-Rate Guarantees\n\n**Terminal Predictor Bound (Theorem 2):**\nWith probability ≥ 1 − δ_V − δ:\n```\nR[h_T] ≤ inf_{h ∈ G_K[m]} R[h] + Õ[√((K[m] + log(1/δ))/m)]\n```\n\nThis is \"the standard VC rate\" applied post-self-modification. Each accepted edit monotonically reduces true risk by ≥ τ on the high-probability event.\n\n---\n\n## (5) Practical Capacity Proxies for Policy/Prompt Edits\n\nThe paper does not provide explicit proxies for language models or prompt engineering. For neural networks, it notes: \"for ReLU networks, B[Z] = c·W[Z]·log(W[Z])\" where W[Z] is parameter count.\n\nFor policy or prompt modifications, the authors do not offer domain-specific proxies, leaving this as an open implementation question.\n\n---\n\n## (6) Capacity Schedule Growing with Data\n\n**Specification:**\nK[m] is nondecreasing and chosen proportionally to available data. The paper states: \"the capacity schedule K[m] can grow with accumulating data, enabling unbounded absolute improvement while maintaining learnability.\"\n\n**Implication:**\nNo explicit functional form is given, but K[m] must grow slowly enough that the VC rate √[K[m]/m] remains manageable."}]},"uuid":"17532529-1571-419d-87d0-534fa764f3a9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T04:16:01.290Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":486945,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Two-Gate Policy and Capacity-Bounded Self-Modification\n\n## (1) Two-Gate Policy: Validation and Capacity Gates\n\n**Validation Gate (Validation Margin):**\nAn edit is accepted only if:\n```\nR̂_V[h_new] ≤ R̂_V[h_old] − [2ε_V + τ]\n```\n\nwhere ε_V satisfies:\n```\nsup_{h ∈ G_K[m]} |R[h] − R̂_V[h]| ≤ ε_V\n```\n\nwith probability ≥ 1 − δ_V over validation samples. The paper specifies that \"ε_V ≍ √[(K[m] + log(1/δ_V))/n_v]\" by classical VC uniform convergence bounds.\n\nThe margin τ ≥ 0 is user-specified; each accepted edit must reduce empirical validation risk by at least the noise floor plus the stability margin.\n\n**Capacity Gate (Capacity Cap):**\n```\nh_new ∈ G_K[m]  and  VC[G_K[m]] ≤ K[m]\n```\n\nThe capped reference family G_K[m] is fixed before observing validation data. Only edits producing hypotheses within this family are permitted.\n\n---\n\n## (2) Operational Capacity Bounding\n\n**Capacity Cap Schedule K[m]:**\nThe paper defines K[·] as a \"nondecreasing capacity cap schedule at sample size m.\" The schedule grows with available training data, enabling \"unbounded absolute improvement while maintaining learnability.\"\n\n**Proxy-Based Enforcement (Architectural Case):**\nFor systems where true VC dimension is intractable, a computable upper-bound proxy B[Z] replaces direct VC measurement:\n```\nVC[H[Z]] ≤ B[Z]  for all Z ∈ Z\n```\n\nThe proxy-capped subfamily is then:\n```\nG^proxy_K = {h ∈ G: ∃Z with B[Z] ≤ K and h ∈ H[Z]}\n```\n\nOnly edits satisfying B[Z_new] ≤ K[m] are accepted.\n\n---\n\n## (3) Utility-Learnability Tension (Core Theorem 1)\n\n**Statement:**\n\"Distribution-free PAC learnability is preserved under representational self-modification if and only if sup_{H' ∈ H_reach[u]} VC[H'] < ∞.\"\n\n**Tension Mechanism:**\nUtilities that reward empirical fit and capacity growth can drive policy-reachable VC unbounded. The paper proves: \"when capacity can grow without limit, utility-rational self-changes can render learnable tasks unlearnable.\" Even local capacity increases compounding across iterations destroy distribution-free guarantees.\n\n---\n\n## (4) Oracle Inequality and VC-Rate Guarantees\n\n**Terminal Predictor Bound (Theorem 2):**\nWith probability ≥ 1 − δ_V − δ:\n```\nR[h_T] ≤ inf_{h ∈ G_K[m]} R[h] + Õ[√((K[m] + log(1/δ))/m)]\n```\n\nThis is \"the standard VC rate\" applied post-self-modification. Each accepted edit monotonically reduces true risk by ≥ τ on the high-probability event.\n\n---\n\n## (5) Practical Capacity Proxies for Policy/Prompt Edits\n\nThe paper does not provide explicit proxies for language models or prompt engineering. For neural networks, it notes: \"for ReLU networks, B[Z] = c·W[Z]·log(W[Z])\" where W[Z] is parameter count.\n\nFor policy or prompt modifications, the authors do not offer domain-specific proxies, leaving this as an open implementation question.\n\n---\n\n## (6) Capacity Schedule Growing with Data\n\n**Specification:**\nK[m] is nondecreasing and chosen proportionally to available data. The paper states: \"the capacity schedule K[m] can grow with accumulating data, enabling unbounded absolute improvement while maintaining learnability.\"\n\n**Implication:**\nNo explicit functional form is given, but K[m] must grow slowly enough that the VC rate √[K[m]/m] remains manageable.","durationMs":13656,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.04399v2"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b667c2c0-90af-4e86-836e-43a75793e709","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
